Part 1: Customizing Layouts<br>
<br>
     In Painter 7, there's a few very useful little tricks in the realm of customizing your workspace.  First off: turning on and off palettes: ctrl-1 will get yuor toolbar, ctrl-2 your brushes box, ctrl-3 the art materials, ctril-4 the objects (layers and such), ctrl-5 your tool-specific controls (the little box with size and opacity), ctril-6 your color set, and ctrl-7 your brush controls.  Makes things go much faster.  But wait, there's more.<br>
<br>
     Set up your screen in whatever way you prefer to have it most of the time, with the locations of the palettes, which ones are up, and et cetera.  Got it right?  Good.  Now, go up to Window&gt;Arrange Palettes&gt;Save Layout.  Save your layout as whatever, and now you can load that configuration up.  Isn't that cool?  You can save a different layout up for pencil drawing, painting, layer editing, and et cetera, and just load each one up as you need them.<br>
<br>
     Incidentally, if you have two monitors and a PC with Painter, the only way to put your toolbars on the second monitor is to actually resize the Painter program to encompass both monitors - do the non-maximized, non-minimized thingy, grab the edge of the program, and drag it into your other monitor. <br>
<br>
Part 2: Custom Toolbars<br>
<br>
     This is very easy.  Grab one of your brushes from the Brushes palette, and drag it out of the palette.  It'll form a nifty NEW palette, which saves automatically.  Go to Window&gt;Custom Palette to load them up.  <br>
     In addition, in Window&gt;Custom Palette, there's another command: Add Command.  Select this, and select which toolbar you want to add a command to.  Then go to whatever menu command, in any palette or the top-of-the-screen menus that you want, and select it.  That menu command will be added to the toolbar.  For example, say I like to use Motion Blur a lot.  I'll make me a new toolbar, and go to Add Command.  Then, I'll go to Effects&gt;Focus&gt;Motion Blur... while the Add Command dialogue box is up, and it will add Motion Blur... as a command in my toolbar.  Now, instead of going up to the drop-down menu, I just click &quot;Motion Blur...&quot; in my custom toolbar.<br>
<br>
That is all.<br>
